<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Probably native to tropical America (
<bibRefCitation author="Wood, SL" journalOrPublisher="The Great Basin Naturalist" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="67 - 74" refId="B481" refString="Wood, SL, 1977. Introduced and exported American Scolytidae (Coleoptera). The Great Basin Naturalist 37: 67 - 74" title="Introduced and exported American Scolytidae (Coleoptera)." volume="37" year="1977">Wood 1977</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1186/s12862-016-0610-7" author="Gohli, J" journalOrPublisher="BMC Evolutionary Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 37" refId="B171" refString="Gohli, J, Selvarajah, T, Kirkendall, LR, Jordal, BH, 2016. Globally distributed Xyleborus species reveal recurrent intercontinental dispersal in a landscape of ancient worldwide distributions. BMC Evolutionary Biology 16: 1 - 37, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1186/s12862-016-0610-7" title="Globally distributed Xyleborus species reveal recurrent intercontinental dispersal in a landscape of ancient worldwide distributions." url="https://doi.org/10.1186/s12862-016-0610-7" volume="16" year="2016">Gohli et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
), but now in temperate and tropical regions around the world. Less common in the Oriental region than in Africa and the Americas, but sometimes locally abundant. Recorded in the study region from Cambodia*, China* (Hainan, Yunnan), India (Meghalaya*, Tamil Nadu*, no state recorded), Laos*, Myanmar*, Nepal, Taiwan, Thailand, Vietnam*.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
