<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The biology of the species is reviewed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Schedl, KE" journalOrPublisher="Revista de Entomologia de Mocambique" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 594" refId="B399" refString="Schedl, KE, 1963a. Scolytidae und Platypodidae Afrikas. Band II. Familie Scolytidae (Fortsetzung), Unterfamilie Ipinae (Fortsetzung). Revista de Entomologia de Mocambique 5: 1 - 594" title="Scolytidae und Platypodidae Afrikas. Band II. Familie Scolytidae (Fortsetzung), Unterfamilie Ipinae (Fortsetzung)." volume="5" year="1963 a">Schedl (1963a)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/entom.gen/12/1987/267" author="Schneider, I" journalOrPublisher="The Coleopterists Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B431" refString="Schneider, I, 1987. Verbreitung, Pilzuebertragung und Brutsystem des Ambrosiakaefers Xyleborusaffinis im vergleich mit X.mascarensis (Coleoptera: Scolytidae) Entomologia Generalis 12: 267-275. https://doi.org/10.1127/entom.gen/12/1987/267" title="Verbreitung, Pilzuebertragung und Brutsystem des Ambrosiakaefers Xyleborusaffinis im vergleich mit X. mascarensis (Coleoptera: Scolytidae) Entomologia Generalis 12: 267 - 275." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/entom.gen/12/1987/267" year="1987">Schneider (1987)</bibRefCitation>
notes that more than one generation may inhabit the same gallery system, and describes the oral mycangia. Seasonal changes in numbers caught in traps have been related to temperature and rainfall in Africa (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1439-0418.1991.tb01084.x" author="Beaver, RA" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Applied Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="505 - 511" refId="B24" refString="Beaver, RA, Loeyttyniemi, K, 1991. Annual flight patterns and diversity of bark and ambrosia beetles (Col., Scolytidae and Platypodidae) attracted to bait logs in Zambia. Journal of Applied Entomology 112: 505 - 511, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1439-0418.1991.tb01084.x" title="Annual flight patterns and diversity of bark and ambrosia beetles (Col., Scolytidae and Platypodidae) attracted to bait logs in Zambia." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1439-0418.1991.tb01084.x" volume="112" year="1991">
Beaver and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Löyttyniemi">Loeyttyniemi</normalizedToken>
1991
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00382167.1995.9629684" author="Madoffe, S" journalOrPublisher="South African Forestry Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="9 - 15" refId="B251" refString="Madoffe, S, Bakke, A, 1995. Seasonal fluctuations and diversity of bark and wood-boring beetles in lowland forest: implications for management practices. South African Forestry Journal 173: 9 - 15, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00382167.1995.9629684" title="Seasonal fluctuations and diversity of bark and wood-boring beetles in lowland forest: implications for management practices." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00382167.1995.9629684" volume="173" year="1995">Madoffe and Bakke 1995</bibRefCitation>
), and in Central America (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.15517/rbt.v60i4.2075" author="Rangel, R" journalOrPublisher="Revista de Biologia Tropical" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1577 - 1588" refId="B323" refString="Rangel, R, Perez, M, Sanchez, S, Capello, S, 2012. Population fluctuation of Xyleborus ferrugineus and X. affinis (Coleoptera: Curculionidae) in ecosystems of Tabasco, Mexico. Revista de Biologia Tropical 60: 1577 - 1588, DOI: https://doi.org/10.15517/rbt.v60i4.2075" title="Population fluctuation of Xyleborus ferrugineus and X. affinis (Coleoptera: Curculionidae) in ecosystems of Tabasco, Mexico." url="https://doi.org/10.15517/rbt.v60i4.2075" volume="60" year="2012">Rangel et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). Flight height preference in Amazonia is described by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1590/1809-43922001311068" author="Abreu, RLS" journalOrPublisher="Acta Amazonica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="61 - 68" refId="B1" refString="Abreu, RLS, Fonseca, CRV, Guerrero, JCH, Paula, EVCM, 2001. Preferencia de voo de nove especies da familia Scolytidae (Insecta: Coleoptera) na Amazonia Central. Acta Amazonica 31: 61 - 68, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1590/1809-43922001311068" title="Preferencia de voo de nove especies da familia Scolytidae (Insecta: Coleoptera) na Amazonia Central." url="https://doi.org/10.1590/1809-43922001311068" volume="31" year="2001">Abreu et al. (2001)</bibRefCitation>
. Laboratory rearing techniques, and the occurrence of delayed dispersal and alloparental care are discussed by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1603/022.038.0417" author="Biedermann, PHW" journalOrPublisher="Environmental Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1096 - 1105" refId="B38" refString="Biedermann, PHW, Klepzig, KR, Taborsky, M, 2009. Fungus cultivation by ambrosia beetles: behavior and laboratory breeding success in three Xyleborine species. Environmental Entomology 38: 1096 - 1105, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1603/022.038.0417" title="Fungus cultivation by ambrosia beetles: behavior and laboratory breeding success in three Xyleborine species." url="https://doi.org/10.1603/022.038.0417" volume="38" year="2009">Biedermann et al. (2009</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00265-011-1183-5" author="Biedermann, PHW" journalOrPublisher="Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1753 - 1761" refId="B39" refString="Biedermann, PHW, Klepzig, KD, Taborsky, M, 2011. Costs of delayed dispersal and alloparental care in the fungus-cultivating ambrosia beetle Xyleborus affinis Eichhoff (Scolytinae: Curculionidae). Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology 65: 1753 - 1761, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s00265-011-1183-5" title="Costs of delayed dispersal and alloparental care in the fungus-cultivating ambrosia beetle Xyleborus affinis Eichhoff (Scolytinae: Curculionidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00265-011-1183-5" volume="65" year="2011">2011</bibRefCitation>
). Although its attacks are secondary, the species can be of economic importance due to its abundance and wide host range.
</paragraph>
